1
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:14,100
(suspenseful music playing)

2
00:00:41,970 --> 00:00:44,020
(suspenseful music continues)

3
00:02:01,130 --> 00:02:04,000
(suspenseful music continues)

4
00:03:51,030 --> 00:03:52,170
And if there's
anything you need to--

5
00:03:52,170 --> 00:03:54,950
How do I get long distance
if I use my card?

6
00:03:54,950 --> 00:03:58,030
Seven, one, area code
and number.

7
00:03:58,030 --> 00:03:59,100
Do you want any lights?

8
00:03:59,100 --> 00:04:00,930
(phone keys clicking)

9
00:04:00,930 --> 00:04:03,000
You can do
your express check-out
with the TV,

10
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,010
-and if you want anything
from the mini-bar--
-Jerry.

11
00:04:05,190 --> 00:04:07,010
Rocky Carleson.

12
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,120
Yeah, I made it on one piece,
but it was like flying on rocks.

13
00:04:11,950 --> 00:04:12,970
Look,

14
00:04:12,970 --> 00:04:14,090
I've never seen
this kind of heat

15
00:04:14,090 --> 00:04:16,070
in all the years
I've been Bill Palmer's agent.

16
00:04:16,070 --> 00:04:18,990
I'm telling you,
this is a marked change.

17
00:04:19,150 --> 00:04:20,920
So listen...

18
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:22,100
I'm two meetings away
from seeing Bill,

19
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:24,150
I want to find out
if we are doing
any paperback business,

20
00:04:24,150 --> 00:04:25,930
-so I can tell him...
-(suspenseful music plays)

21
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,930
(sirens blaring in distance)

22
00:04:28,930 --> 00:04:30,160
(laughs) Yeah.

23
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:31,990
It could be meaningful.

24
00:04:32,950 --> 00:04:35,010
What do I mean meaningful?
What do you think I mean?

25
00:04:36,010 --> 00:04:38,020
I'm getting
picture offers already.

26
00:04:39,170 --> 00:04:41,170
And we're only taking
a million five from your end

27
00:04:41,170 --> 00:04:43,000
to start the conversation.

28
00:04:43,160 --> 00:04:44,980
And then you own a property
that ties

29
00:04:44,980 --> 00:04:47,160
into a fucking tailor-made
Michael Douglas vehicle.

30
00:04:49,910 --> 00:04:51,940
It's just that
a fact's a fact, Jerry.

31
00:04:51,940 --> 00:04:53,970
Other people know
they want the package,

32
00:04:53,970 --> 00:04:55,960
I'm just thinking
of our prior relationship.

33
00:04:56,080 --> 00:04:57,090
Exactly.

34
00:04:58,980 --> 00:05:01,100
You work your number.
I'll call you in, uh...

35
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:02,940
three hours.

36
00:05:03,190 --> 00:05:05,110
Good, good.

37
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:08,900
And trust me on this one.

38
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:09,950
I'm not bluffing.

39
00:05:16,970 --> 00:05:18,050
(thud)

40
00:05:21,050 --> 00:05:23,160
[anchorwoman] New today,
Bone Daddy,

41
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:25,950
latest page-turner
from Chicago's

42
00:05:25,950 --> 00:05:28,080
master of the macabre,
William Palmer.

43
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:31,990
A man who, as residents
of the windy city will remember,

44
00:05:31,990 --> 00:05:34,020
knows exactly
what he's talking about

45
00:05:34,020 --> 00:05:38,030
when it comes to matters
of the no longer beating heart.

46
00:05:38,030 --> 00:05:40,010
This is because his last day job

47
00:05:40,010 --> 00:05:43,970
was as Chief Medical Examiner
of Chicago.

48
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:47,060
Chicagoans will recall
the real Bone Daddy
serial murder case

49
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:48,910
of seven years ago,

50
00:05:48,910 --> 00:05:51,140
in which the perpetrator
was never caught.

51
00:05:51,140 --> 00:05:52,970
In Palmer's new book,

52
00:05:52,970 --> 00:05:54,910
he's written
a fictionalized account

53
00:05:54,910 --> 00:05:57,050
in which the killer is caught.

54
00:05:59,070 --> 00:06:02,020
While in Chicago,
Palmer won headlines galore

55
00:06:02,020 --> 00:06:04,170
and notoriety
among criminologists

56
00:06:04,170 --> 00:06:06,980
for cracking
any number of famous

57
00:06:06,980 --> 00:06:09,070
and complex murder cases.

58
00:06:09,070 --> 00:06:10,930
So like his others,

59
00:06:10,930 --> 00:06:12,090
this latest book will, no doubt,

60
00:06:12,090 --> 00:06:15,060
crackle
with nail-biting intensity.

61
00:06:15,060 --> 00:06:17,920
For Chicago Today,
I'm Marilyn Chalmers.

62
00:06:21,910 --> 00:06:24,110
(seagulls squawking)

63
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:31,170
(traffic buzzing)

64
00:06:37,140 --> 00:06:39,080
(indistinct chatter)

65
00:06:39,080 --> 00:06:41,030
(soft music playing)

66
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:20,970
-I even spelled it right.
-Thank you.

67
00:07:20,970 --> 00:07:22,150
It's to Patti.

68
00:07:24,110 --> 00:07:27,010
Excuse me, excuse me, folks,
excuse me.

69
00:07:27,010 --> 00:07:28,180
Excuse me, thank you.

70
00:07:28,180 --> 00:07:29,970
Thank you very much,
ladies and gentlemen,

71
00:07:29,970 --> 00:07:31,180
that's all the time Dr. Palmer
has for today.

72
00:07:31,990 --> 00:07:34,150
Sorry to disappoint,
but if I don't get him
to his next appointment on time,

73
00:07:34,980 --> 00:07:36,020
I'll lose my job.

74
00:07:36,930 --> 00:07:37,970
You have 40 minutes.

75
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:40,920
I can't be late
for Peter's party.

76
00:07:41,110 --> 00:07:42,160
Where's Rocky?

77
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:44,910
Quit worrying. Hi. Hi.

78
00:07:44,910 --> 00:07:46,010
I need to talk to him.

79
00:07:46,010 --> 00:07:47,080
Sorry.

80
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:48,980
-Everything is under control.
-You sure?

81
00:07:48,980 --> 00:07:50,970
I'm sure. That's how P.R. people
keep their job.

82
00:07:50,970 --> 00:07:52,910
We make sure
before you even think of it.

83
00:07:52,910 --> 00:07:54,960
I thought it was by doing P.R.

84
00:07:55,080 --> 00:07:56,140
That is P.R.

85
00:08:00,060 --> 00:08:01,910
[man] I'll try Rocky again.

86
00:08:02,980 --> 00:08:04,180
[Bill] Can I tell you a secret?

87
00:08:04,180 --> 00:08:05,990
[man] You don't have to.
I already know.

88
00:08:07,070 --> 00:08:09,140
Hi, Rocky Carleson, please,
room 878.

89
00:08:09,140 --> 00:08:11,970
You're nervous having your kid
one jump away from your old job.

90
00:08:13,120 --> 00:08:15,990
You know what, you could
really piss a person off.

91
00:08:16,180 --> 00:08:17,920
[man] It's busy again.

92
00:08:18,040 --> 00:08:19,140
We'll pick him up on the way.

93
00:08:23,080 --> 00:08:25,010
(horns honking)

94
00:08:29,100 --> 00:08:31,110
[Bill] Rocky? (clears throat)
Are you in there?

95
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:33,180
Nobody in here but me.

96
00:08:33,180 --> 00:08:35,940
Wasn't nobody here
when I came either.

97
00:08:37,910 --> 00:08:40,120
I'm sorry, Donna, is it?
Can we look inside?

98
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:41,120
-Thanks a lot.
-(phone beeping)

99
00:08:42,090 --> 00:08:44,070
[Bill] No wonder it was busy.

100
00:08:44,070 --> 00:08:45,110
(phone clicks)

101
00:08:45,110 --> 00:08:46,940
Phone is off the damn hook.

102
00:08:47,910 --> 00:08:48,950
Rocky?

103
00:08:49,190 --> 00:08:50,940
[man] Nice room.

104
00:08:52,110 --> 00:08:53,920
Yeah, there's his bag.

105
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:55,090
I'm really not supposed
to let you in here

106
00:08:55,090 --> 00:08:56,150
if it's not your room.

107
00:08:56,150 --> 00:08:57,940
It's so unlike him.

108
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:01,070
-(bin clatters)
-[Donna] Don't know
how that happened.

109
00:09:01,070 --> 00:09:02,930
Never happened before.

110
00:09:02,930 --> 00:09:05,970
But, you know,
room service chicken's
awful popular.

111
00:09:08,100 --> 00:09:09,130
Thank you, Donna.

112
00:09:12,070 --> 00:09:14,920
(suspenseful music playing)

113
00:09:29,970 --> 00:09:30,990
Middle finger.

114
00:09:32,960 --> 00:09:34,060
Left hand.

115
00:09:37,160 --> 00:09:39,030
(siren wailing)

116
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:47,910
[man 1] What if the Bone Daddy
could be back?

117
00:09:49,030 --> 00:09:50,170
To tell you the truth,

118
00:09:51,940 --> 00:09:54,110
I started to worry
when I heard the goddamn title.

119
00:09:55,980 --> 00:09:57,130
What's that supposed to mean?

120
00:09:58,980 --> 00:10:01,930
You took a huge risk
and you know it.

121
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:03,900
Could it be a P.R. stunt?

122
00:10:04,080 --> 00:10:06,080
That's completely insulting.

123
00:10:06,080 --> 00:10:08,020
[man 2] How about a fan
paying homage?

124
00:10:08,020 --> 00:10:10,060
My agent may be in danger,

125
00:10:10,060 --> 00:10:12,050
you've got to let me in on this.

126
00:10:12,050 --> 00:10:13,960
-You've been out of it too long.
-Nonsense.

127
00:10:13,960 --> 00:10:15,920
You're also still
pretty fucking arrogant.

128
00:10:16,120 --> 00:10:17,910
Which is one
of his better traits.

129
00:10:17,910 --> 00:10:19,090
[Bill] We were both
on this case before.

130
00:10:20,060 --> 00:10:21,940
I know this man.

131
00:10:23,930 --> 00:10:24,990
And so do you.

132
00:10:29,940 --> 00:10:30,940
All right.

133
00:10:32,130 --> 00:10:33,990
I'll let you work with Hewlett.

134
00:10:35,180 --> 00:10:37,920
-Chief.
-She's the cop.

135
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:39,920
You're the consultant.

136
00:10:39,920 --> 00:10:41,080
Consultant.

137
00:10:46,040 --> 00:10:47,050
Do you understand?

138
00:10:51,940 --> 00:10:53,990
Now, don't you have
a party to get to?

139
00:10:59,140 --> 00:11:02,030
They probably told you
what a grouch I was?

140
00:11:02,030 --> 00:11:03,920
Didn't really do you justice.

141
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:05,110
Spoken like a badge.

142
00:11:06,080 --> 00:11:07,920
How does a badge sound?

143
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:09,100
Depends.

144
00:11:10,100 --> 00:11:12,910
Some of your colleagues
used to have problems with me.

145
00:11:13,080 --> 00:11:15,110
They called you
Dr. Frankenstein.

146
00:11:15,110 --> 00:11:16,150
That is correct.

147
00:11:16,150 --> 00:11:18,930
Well, at least he was smart.

148
00:11:19,990 --> 00:11:21,070
[Bill] They tell you
to flatter me?

149
00:11:21,070 --> 00:11:22,940
[Sharon] Yeah,
but I didn't pay attention.

150
00:11:24,170 --> 00:11:26,110
I know this is all a bit sudden,

151
00:11:26,110 --> 00:11:28,180
and it's probably not the job
you've been dreaming of.

152
00:11:28,180 --> 00:11:31,110
But since you're so brilliant,
I'm supposed to take you
seriously, right?

153
00:11:31,110 --> 00:11:33,000
That would be good.

154
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:35,100
I have an ex-husband
with that attitude.

155
00:11:37,100 --> 00:11:38,940
[Bill] Marriage is hard.

156
00:11:38,940 --> 00:11:40,100
Especially for cops.

157
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:41,950
Yeah, it was hard all around.

158
00:11:43,160 --> 00:11:44,190
Any children?

159
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:46,980
-No.
-You didn't want them?

160
00:11:47,130 --> 00:11:48,150
Excuse me.

161
00:11:51,180 --> 00:11:53,930
Just trying to find out
who I am working with.

162
00:11:53,930 --> 00:11:56,950
Look, it may come
as a surprise to you,

163
00:11:56,950 --> 00:11:58,100
but I've done this before.

164
00:12:00,020 --> 00:12:02,930
I don't like
your defensive attitude.

165
00:12:03,100 --> 00:12:05,020
It doesn't mean
that you're offended,

166
00:12:05,020 --> 00:12:06,950
it means you are insecure.

167
00:12:07,930 --> 00:12:09,940
You can't afford that
on this case.

168
00:12:11,930 --> 00:12:13,140
You hesitate, you lose.

169
00:12:15,910 --> 00:12:17,980
-(door opens)
-(gravel crunching)

170
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:25,920
(orchestral music playing)

171
00:12:29,910 --> 00:12:32,030
(indistinct chatter)

172
00:12:38,130 --> 00:12:39,190
(music stops)

173
00:12:42,160 --> 00:12:44,140
Ladies, gentlemen,
I'd like to...

174
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:46,920
uh, propose a toast to the man

175
00:12:46,920 --> 00:12:48,190
that we are here
to congratulate tonight,

176
00:12:49,070 --> 00:12:50,980
-Peter Palmer.
-[guests] Hear, hear!

177
00:12:50,980 --> 00:12:52,090
(all applaud)

178
00:12:53,990 --> 00:12:55,170
Now, Peter is the kind of man

179
00:12:55,170 --> 00:12:57,970
who will elevate
the medical examiner's office

180
00:12:57,970 --> 00:13:00,010
in this city to better things.

181
00:13:00,010 --> 00:13:02,160
And just like his father,

182
00:13:02,160 --> 00:13:05,090
my very good friend,
Bill Palmer,

183
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:07,130
just like Bill,

184
00:13:07,130 --> 00:13:10,030
Peter will make
a great contribution

185
00:13:10,030 --> 00:13:12,170
and I wouldn't be surprised
one day to hand my job
over to him.

186
00:13:12,170 --> 00:13:14,180
-(guests laugh)
-Watch it.

187
00:13:14,180 --> 00:13:17,910
'Cause I could do that
with complete trust

188
00:13:17,910 --> 00:13:19,030
and confidence.

189
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:21,910
Ladies and gentlemen,
Peter Palmer.

190
00:13:21,910 --> 00:13:23,120
[all] To Peter!

191
00:13:23,120 --> 00:13:26,070
-(guests applauding)
-Thank you very much.

192
00:13:28,120 --> 00:13:29,170
(dog barking in distance)

193
00:13:51,980 --> 00:13:53,120
[butler] Mr. Palmer Sr.
just arrived.

194
00:13:55,940 --> 00:13:56,950
Bill!

195
00:13:57,950 --> 00:14:00,050
You had us watching
the clock there, buddy.

196
00:14:00,050 --> 00:14:02,900
There was a bit of a delay.
I'm sure you've heard.

197
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:04,900
(softly) Yeah, I know,
I got the call.
Are you all right?

198
00:14:04,900 --> 00:14:05,910
I'm fine.

199
00:14:05,990 --> 00:14:07,910
Oh, excuse me, this is...

200
00:14:07,910 --> 00:14:09,060
Detective Sharon Hewlett.

201
00:14:09,060 --> 00:14:10,100
Marshall Stone.

202
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:11,170
Here I thought
she was just another

203
00:14:11,170 --> 00:14:13,060
naive, misguided girl.

204
00:14:14,020 --> 00:14:15,900
Listen, I've got guests, uh...

205
00:14:15,900 --> 00:14:16,940
Peter's in there.

206
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,970
(indistinct chatter)

207
00:14:27,970 --> 00:14:29,930
-[Bill] Peter.
-Hi.

208
00:14:31,110 --> 00:14:32,140
Congratulations.

209
00:14:33,050 --> 00:14:34,070
I'm sorry I'm late.

210
00:14:34,970 --> 00:14:37,140
It's okay, he has been
quite busy with all of this.

211
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:39,920
When you get the job,
you get the job.

212
00:14:40,080 --> 00:14:42,140
That's probably why
they decided to have the party

213
00:14:42,140 --> 00:14:44,050
at the boss's house, right?

214
00:14:44,050 --> 00:14:45,940
You know,
you've made your appearance.

215
00:14:45,940 --> 00:14:48,040
You don't have to hang around
if you're not in the mood.

216
00:14:49,900 --> 00:14:52,000
Photographer needs you
by the cake, champ.

217
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,010
Sorry.

218
00:14:55,170 --> 00:14:57,140
When you get the job,
you get the cake.

219
00:14:59,160 --> 00:15:01,020
The kids said to say hi.

220
00:15:01,150 --> 00:15:02,160
Thank you.

221
00:15:05,030 --> 00:15:06,060
(sighs)

222
00:15:06,060 --> 00:15:08,050
You're obviously
very proud of him.

223
00:15:08,910 --> 00:15:09,920
Yes.

224
00:15:10,900 --> 00:15:12,150
I always knew he'd do well.

225
00:15:14,080 --> 00:15:15,960
Did you have
anything to do with it?

226
00:15:25,150 --> 00:15:26,990
Get a close-up of the cake.

227
00:15:26,990 --> 00:15:28,160
Get a really nice one
of the cake.

228
00:15:30,030 --> 00:15:31,940
-Dr. Palmer.
-Trent!

229
00:15:32,070 --> 00:15:33,930
How have you been?

230
00:15:33,930 --> 00:15:35,910
You're looking
like a million bucks.

231
00:15:35,910 --> 00:15:38,970
Looks deceive. Still making
Y cuts for chump-change.

232
00:15:39,970 --> 00:15:41,150
How's my kid doing?

233
00:15:41,150 --> 00:15:43,080
He inherited the talent.

234
00:15:43,080 --> 00:15:44,170
Keep an eye on him?

235
00:15:44,170 --> 00:15:45,910
Count on it.

236
00:15:52,140 --> 00:15:53,160
[woman] Bill.

237
00:15:53,160 --> 00:15:55,930
I came to share
in the glory too.

238
00:15:56,110 --> 00:15:58,010
That must be because
you're his mother.

239
00:15:58,010 --> 00:15:59,080
Must be.

240
00:16:02,940 --> 00:16:03,970
Who's the brunette?

241
00:16:04,910 --> 00:16:05,940
Come on.

242
00:16:06,110 --> 00:16:08,140
-How are you?
-Excellent.

243
00:16:09,910 --> 00:16:11,000
Don't tell me.

244
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:12,060
I won't.

245
00:16:13,970 --> 00:16:15,190
It's a shame
you missed the toast.

246
00:16:15,190 --> 00:16:17,910
-We waited as long as we could.
-Is this from you, Trent?

247
00:16:18,900 --> 00:16:21,010
You know what a ham
Marshall Stone is.

248
00:16:26,190 --> 00:16:28,010
[Peter] Oh, they're great.

249
00:16:29,020 --> 00:16:30,110
(sighs)

250
00:16:30,950 --> 00:16:32,080
Look at him.

251
00:16:34,060 --> 00:16:37,030
I have just realized,
he's not a kid anymore.

252
00:16:40,900 --> 00:16:42,020
I had always hoped

253
00:16:42,020 --> 00:16:44,920
his life wouldn't be
quite so involved with death.

254
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:46,970
He's not involved with death.

255
00:16:47,980 --> 00:16:49,070
He serves life,

256
00:16:49,070 --> 00:16:51,120
because he studies
the end of it.

257
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:52,120
Ah...

258
00:16:53,060 --> 00:16:54,960
-You're as good as ever.
-Don't.

259
00:16:55,180 --> 00:16:56,960
Never better.

260
00:16:56,960 --> 00:16:58,910
Never covers a lot of ground.

261
00:17:09,070 --> 00:17:10,090
Ex-wife?

262
00:17:10,980 --> 00:17:12,070
Yes.

263
00:17:12,070 --> 00:17:13,140
Twelve years.

